President Obama announced his intent to nominate several individuals to key administration posts. Elaine Schuster, a philanthropist and advocate for healthcare and education, was nominated as the Representative of the United States of America to the Sixty-fourth Session of the General Assembly of the United Nations. Laura Gore Ross, an attorney and member of the board of directors of the Mayor's Fund to Advance New York City, was nominated as the Alternate Representative of the United States of America to the Sixty-fourth Session of the General Assembly of the United Nations. Wellington E. Webb, former Mayor of Denver, was nominated as the Alternate Representative of the United States of America to the Sixty-fourth Session of the General Assembly of the United Nations. Congressman William Delahunt, a member of the House Committee on Foreign Affairs, was nominated as the Representative of the United States of America to the Sixty-fourth Session of the General Assembly of the United Nations. Congressman Chris Smith, a senior Republican member of the House Committee on Foreign Affairs, was nominated as the Representative of the United States of America to the Sixty-fourth Session of the General Assembly of the United Nations. Mary Warlick, a career member of the Senior Foreign Service, was nominated as the Ambassador to the Republic of Serbia. Islam A. Siddiqui, currently Vice President for Science and Regulatory Affairs at CropLife America, was nominated as the Chief Agricultural Negotiator in the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative. Alan D. Bersin, Assistant Secretary for International Affairs and Special Representative for Border Affairs in the Department of Homeland Security, was nominated as the Commissioner of U.S. Customs and Border Protection. President Obama expressed gratitude to these individuals for their willingness to serve and expressed confidence in their ability to represent the nation well.